althy areas in Britain. It presents explanations for the widening health gap, and addresses the implications of this major social problem. In the light of this evidence the authors put forward social policies which will reduce the health gap in the future. The widening gap synthesises all the information available to date and should be read alongside the report of the evidence presented to the Independent Inquiry into Inequalities in Health (Inequalities in health, The Policy Press, 1999) and by all those concerned with reducing health inequalities. Studies in poverty, inequality and social exclusion series Series Editor: David Gordon, Director, Townsend Centre for International Poverty Research. Poverty, inequality and social exclusion remain the most fundamental problems that humanity faces in the 21st century. This exciting series, published in association with the Townsend Centre for International Poverty Research at the University of Bristol, aims to make cutting-edge poverty related research more widely available. For other titles in this series, please follow the series link from the main catalogue page.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mai 2023) 0aEqualityzGreat Britain. 0aPublic healthzGreat Britain. 7aMEDICAL / Health Policy.2bisacsh1 aDorling, Daniel, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aGordon, David, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aTownsend, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBristol University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2013-1995z97831111962130 cprintz978186134142640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781847425072423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781847425072/original  a978-3-11-119621-3  Bristol University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2013-